name: spaces/AAAAocwPEic/messages/vIgQ93dfcKg.3tBWUv8P9co
text:
Hi  @Kevin Susanto to answer your questions
1. if today is 2 Aug 2024, that means history data for 1 year from 2 Aug 2023 - 2 Aug 2024 is the one that is going to be loaded
yes if on 2 Aug Looker return exactly 1 year of data up to the date. Full refresh in Looker querying context is we request every rows that Looker is currently storing at the request time.
2. this 1 year data will then be snapshotted in GCS
if you go through the pipeline code, everything returned from looker is first stored in GCS then loaded to BQ --> so yes to this also.
3. the history table will be deleted all entries and being refreshed to that 1 year data only?
No, we will base on the ID of each row and will do an append of no matching on ID and overwrite the row when match --> no deletion is happening in the process and the logic of is_deleted we will have to base on the native column from Looker or if the col doesn't exist and the table is in full refresh then base on the loaded_at maximum value to determine is_deleted

Hi Kevin,
The row count test we did was under the assumption that Looker only retains the records within a 1 year period for this view. Therefore, with the filter of cursor_field's value in between the test runtime and that runtime -1 year. This means that every day we were looking at a moving 1 year window of row count data --> So the delta of one day to the next should be the the different in row count between the first day of the previous window and the last (or current day) of the following window. Hope this is clear enough.

on the context of history table, on average in the past 3 days, the I column in the sheet indicate the absolute rate of discrepancy - which could be, and these are not mutually exclusive, both can be the case on a single test
    1. we extract more rows than Looker currently has at testing time --> Looker removed rows belong in the past 3 days

text:
Hi Kevin, it would seem that the explore dashboard (which contains the views like dashboard, dashboard_element,....) has an `always_filter` on `dashboard.moved_to_trash = No`, this would mean that yes even in full refresh mode, the views under this explore will always have this filter on. 
We encountered this previously with views from the explore `user` before so the fix has been implemented for some of these views.
what you have to do is in the `schema.yml` file update the parameter `filter:` with `dashboard.moved_to_trash: ""` for `dashboard_element` (or up to you, all views under dashboard explore) to override this `always_filter` setting in the native System Activity. Then all rows should be extracting correctly.
you can find the example i did for `user` explore's view in the screenshot below. `schema.yml:line4547`. Also please ping me to review if everything is good before merging.
